  "prompt": "What can cause astigmatism?",
  "response": "Astigmatism is primarily caused by an **irregular curvature of the cornea**, the clear front surface of the eye. Instead of being perfectly round like a baseball, it's shaped more like a football. This irregular shape prevents light from focusing properly on the retina, resulting in blurry or distorted vision at all distances.\n\nHere's a breakdown of the main causes:\n\n*   **Corneal Astigmatism (Most Common):**\n\n    *   **Heredity (Genetics):**  This is the most significant factor. Astigmatism often runs in families. You are more likely to have it if one or both of your parents have it.\n    *   **Developmental:** The cornea can develop an irregular shape as a person grows. This can occur naturally and without any identifiable external cause.\n\n*   **Lenticular Astigmatism:**\n\n    *   **Lens Abnormalities:**  Less commonly, astigmatism can be caused by irregularities in the shape of the eye's lens, which is located behind the pupil.\n    *   **Cataracts:** Cataracts can sometimes affect the shape of the lens and contribute to astigmatism.\n\n*   **Other Causes (Less Common):**\n\n    *   **Eye Injuries:** Trauma to the eye or eyelid can distort the shape of the cornea.\n    *   **Eye Surgery:** Some eye surgeries, such as cataract surgery or corneal transplants, can sometimes induce or alter astigmatism.\n    *   **Eye Diseases:** Certain corneal diseases (like keratoconus, where the cornea thins and bulges outward) can cause significant astigmatism.\n    *   **Eyelid Conditions:** Conditions that put pressure on the cornea, like a chalazion or ptosis (drooping eyelid), could potentially contribute.\n    *   **Rarely, certain systemic diseases** can be associated with corneal changes that might include astigmatism.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   Astigmatism is very common and can occur in combination with other refractive errors like nearsightedness (myopia) or farsightedness (hyperopia).\n*   It is usually present from birth or develops early in life, although it can also develop later in life.\n*   It is not caused by reading in dim light, sitting too close to the television, or excessive computer use. These activities can cause eye strain, but they do not change the shape of the cornea.\n*   Astigmatism is easily corrected with eyeglasses, contact lenses, or refractive surgery (like LASIK).\n\nIf you suspect you have astigmatism, it's crucial to see an eye doctor (ophthalmologist or optometrist) for a comprehensive eye exam and proper diagnosis and treatment.\n",
